{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"279ed3d1-08dc-4c6e-976b-9a03986a2e7b","content":"Here's a step-by-step approach:\n\n### 1. Get a shell into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n### 5. Copy the trace off the container\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Tips\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available in the container image, you can download the [standalone `dotnet-trace`](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#install) and copy it in with `kubectl cp`.\n- For Windows containers specifically, ensure the diagnostic IPC channel is available — .NET 8 uses named pipes on Windows (`\\\\.\\pipe\\dotnet-diagnostic-<PID>`).\n- Add `--format speedscope` to get a JSON file you can drag into Speedscope for a quick flamegraph without needing Visual Studio.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"79d675af-27b5-4408-a06e-b25a7e95ceaa","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code change request. I can answer this directly from knowledge.","outputTokens":434},"id":"126b2c62-2ff4-41aa-9b4d-944f67ce914d","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:46:19.902Z","parentId":"e94e1372-9cac-4f72-afe5-d67342e1e080"}
